<HEADLINE>
FT  22 OCT 93 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (1): Slow recovery
has compensations - Keynote / But the stock market, like the economy, is a
more dangerous place than it seems
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HOW MUCH are we willing to pay for security in our investments? As the
markets rose and became still riskier in the third quarter of the year, the
question became more urgent for personal investors.
A different kind of safety has also become a pressing issue for occupational
pension schemes, culminating in the publication of the Goode Report on
pension law reform last month.
For individual savers the big challenge continues to be the shift of
emphasis from nice, safe income to more ephemeral capital gains. True,
short-term interest rates have not fallen since last January in the UK, but
the possibility of a cut keeps re-emerging: Kenneth Clarke, chancellor of
the exchequer, let go his chance of a rate to coincide with the Conservative
Party conference earlier this month, but he will have another opportunity
around Budget Day, November 30.
Meanwhile, long-term interest rates are slipping consistently. The yield on
long-dated government securities slid from 8.1 per cent to 7.3 per cent
during the quarter. The yield on equities also fell, but not so rapidly.
When yields decline in the securities markets, investors are compensated by
the capital gains that are the reverse side of the coin. But the higher that
the markets rise, the greater the natural fear that one day the process will
go into reverse.
The July-September period, however, was a time for greed rather than fear.
Although European politicians generally had a bad and embarrassing summer as
the European Monetary System crumbled around them, investors could relax on
the beach contentedly. Perhaps the sunshine was erratic, but generally the
financial markets were set fair.
London share prices entered new high ground in August, hitting a peak on the
27th. It seemed that the deputy fund managers were a little
over-enthusiastic, though. When their bosses returned at the beginning of
September the market cooled off. Still, the FT-SE 100 Index showed a gain of
4.7 per cent for the three months, its best quarterly showing of 1993 so
far.
Once again, however, the big blue-chips dragged their feet, with
disappointing results coming from the likes of Tesco, Guinness and P&amp;O.
Fearsome levels of competition hit many of the consumer sectors, dashing
hopes that companies would be able to put up prices and restore their profit
margins as the recession came to an end and economic recovery began.
Forecasters have been polishing up their numbers for the UK economy in 1993.
It now looks as though GDP growth may hit nearer 2 per cent than the 1-1 1/2
per cent expected earlier. Yet this is still far from the vigorous
bounce-back from recession that was once typical of the UK's economic cycle.
No sooner had the motor industry celebrated a year-on-year rise of 18 per
cent in 'K' car registrations in August than a series of announcements of
autumn production cutbacks came out, because Continental demand had slumped.
In the US, too, where the recovery has being going on longer, its strength
is still rather disappointing and erratic.
A slow but steady recovery has its compensations. It makes for low
volatility and a stable trend in the securities markets. To make their
fortunes in 1993, investors have had to chase risky recoveries in the
advanced countries (in Italy, say) and hair-raising booms in the developing
world. Nearer home the rewards have been more meagre, but it has been easy
to sleep at night.
The world now looks quite a deflationary place, at least as far as the
advanced economies are concerned. They are flooded with cheap imported goods
from the Far East, holding prices down, and high levels of unemployment are
keeping pay inflation under tight control.
On the one hand, this is excellent news for the bond markets, subject only
to the fear that too many governments maybe unable to restrain their budget
deficits in the recession. Low levels of interest rates and inflation are
also positive for equities. However, if companies are unable to generate at
least a modicum of profits growth and dividend expansion, equities may at
some point look dangerously ahead of the game.
Up to the end of the third quarter, most of the recent trends remained
intact. In particular, small companies continued to outperform, with the
FT-Actuaries SmallCap Index running 2 1/2 percentage points ahead of the
Footsie during the three months (and 23 per cent ahead after nine months of
the year).
The small-company theme is becoming ever more mature, however, and the
average p/e ratio of the constituents of the SmallCap has risen to an
awesome 35. That looks more like Tokyo than London. Such ratings are, not
surprisingly, attracting dozens of new listings as entrepreneurs and
management buy-out teams seek to cash in.
Can an investment in Tiddler plc or Titchy plc pay off at these prices? The
argument runs: first, there is a recovery and those companies that have
survived the recession are lean and fit; and second, small companies usually
operate nimbly in niche markets, whereas too many big companies are
painfully exposed to overcapacity.
Food retailing, for instance, has been the latest to be devastated by the
fear of over-expansion: the sector index underperformed by 17 per cent in
the third quarter, and the sector now offers a market average dividend
yield. Much the same, for slightly different reasons, has happened to the
pharmaceuticals sector.
The stock market, like the economy at large, is therefore a rather more
dangerous place than it appears to be on the surface, where the indices have
shown a fairly steady trend. There is churning and upheaval  - the experts
call it sector rotation  - and you should not take it too much for granted
that whatever stocks did well in the third quarter will still be the stars
of your portfolio by Christmas.
As for the pension schemes, they face the consequences of the discovery that
Robert Maxwell had apparently stolen over Pounds 400m from the pension
schemes in his various companies in the months before he was found dead in
the sea just about two years ago.
The Goode Committee has recommended the setting-up of a new pensions
regulator, and the introduction of a minimum solvency standard to ensure
that schemes can meet their obligations if their sponsoring company suddenly
goes bust. A compensation scheme will bail out victims if there is fraud or
misconduct.
The catch is that a watertight system is expensive to run, and it is much
cheaper to leave some loopholes. When companies failed to protest vigorously
at the impositions of the Goode Report, there were bound to be suspicions
that the committee had bent too far towards compromise. The government still
has to respond. But in pension schemes any degree of risk at all is surely
unacceptable.
</TEXT>
