<HEADLINE>
FT  22 OCT 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow retreats after an opening
upbeat note
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
AMID A flurry of corporate earnings reports and a sell-off in the bond
market, US stock prices retreated yesterday after briefly flirting with
record high levels, writes Frank McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average ended 8.94 easier at 3,636.16 and the
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was off 0.71 at 465.36. Secondary markets were more
resilient, with the American SE composite firming 0.93 to 477.52 and the
Nasdaq composite 3.03 higher at 771.28. NYSE volume was 287.2m shares.
The session opened on an upbeat note following the decision by the German
central bank to cut interest rates by  1/2 percentage point. The move
appeared to improve prospects for US export opportunities to Europe.
However, attention was mostly focused on a rash of quarterly reports, which
were mixed to slightly better than expected, and equities registered early
gains.
As the morning progressed, share prices began to slip into negative
territory, with investors taking their cue from an accelerating sell-off in
US Treasuries. Long-dated bond prices fell sharply after the release of the
Philadelphia Federal Reserve's Business Outlook Survey, which showed a surge
in economic activity in the region. Bond traders interpreted the data as a
signal of renewed inflationary pressure.
In the afternoon, share prices managed to regain momentum before taking a
second downturn in the last hour of trading.
Banking issues were given a boost by a strong earnings report from Bankers
Trust, up Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 79 1/4 after its announcement of an 86 per
cent increase in net income.
The positive sentiment also gave a lift to Chemical, Dollars  5/8 higher at
Dollars 42. Citibank put on Dollars  1/4 at Dollars 37 5/8 and Chase
Manhattan was ahead Dollars  5/8 at Dollars 34 7/8 . Bankamerica recovered
some ground lost in Wednesday's session, rising Dollars 1 to Dollars 43 1/2
.
Dow Chemical was active and tumbled Dollars 2 1/2 to Dollars 56 3/8 , even
though its third-quarter earnings of 50 cents a share were in line with
analysts' expectations.
Caterpillar climbed Dollars 2 3/4 to a 52-week high of Dollars 85 7/8 after
the heavy equipment maker posted third-quarter operating income of 95 cents
a share, well ahead of the consensus forecast of 57 cents.
Telecommunications and technology issues were mixed. AT&amp;T shed Dollars 1 1/4
to Dollars 59 3/4 after reporting that its NCR operation had fallen into
loss in the third quarter.
Contributing to the Nasdaq advance, MCI gained Dollars  5/8 at Dollars 28
1/2 on news of a robust performance in the last three months.
However, Microsoft dropped Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 79 1/2 amid concern over
weakening growth at the software company.
Among energy companies issuing quarterly reports, Amoco declined Dollars 1
1/8 to Dollars 55 5/8 , while Mobil was unchanged at Dollars 80 5/8.
Canada
TORONTO closed lower in busy dealings as the recent rally in gold prices
stalled. The TSE 300 index fell 19 points to 4,163.2. Declining issues
outnumbered advances by 384 to 330. Volume was 63.7m shares.
Ten of the 14 sub-indices declined, led by the gold group, off 2.6 per cent
as the bullion price slipped 70 cents an ounce in New York to USDollars
371.85, after rising about USDollars 8 earlier this week.
