<HEADLINE>
FT  22 OCT 93 / Invergordon loses independence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP RAWSTORNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHYTE &amp; MACKAY, the UK drinks subsidiary of American Brands, has won its
two-year battle to gain control of Invergordon, the independent Scotch
whisky producer.
Invergordon's fate was sealed by the decision of Fleming Investment
Management (FIM) - after two weeks of haggling - to sell its 13.5 per cent
stake for 300p a share. Analysts had expected FIM to hold out for more, but
SG Warburg, FIM's financial adviser, considered 300p 'a good price',
according to Whyte &amp; Mackay.
The deal, which values Invergordon at Pounds 382.4m, lifted Whyte &amp; Mackay's
holding to 54.7 per cent from the 41.2 per cent amassed during its
unsuccessful 1991 bid.
The sale of the FIM stake triggered an unconditional final cash offer of
300p for the rest of the shares.
Invergordon's board, which is advised by Robert Fleming, part of the same
group as FIM, said it was seeking discussions on certain issues - believed
to include the future of the company's management and employees. It urged
shareholders to take no action, and said: 'This price fails to recognise the
strategic value to Whyte &amp; Mackay of Invergordon's business.'
Mr Chris Greig, Invergordon's managing director, said the loss of
independence was 'a great disappointment'. 'I believe that Whyte &amp; Mackay
should have put a formal offer to the board so that the interests of all our
shareholders could be taken into account.
'But one has to face the reality of City situations. FIM was perfectly
entitled to sell its shares.'
Mr Greig, who led the group through a Pounds 93m management buy-out from
Hawker Siddeley in 1988 to a Pounds 172m market flotation two years later,
has a 3.3 per cent stake in the company, now worth about Pounds 12.6m. Other
directors and employees hold a further 7.5 per cent of the equity.
Mr Michael Lunn, Whyte &amp; Mackay's chairman and chief executive, said: 'I
would like an early meeting with Invergordon to see how we can work together
to develop the complementary nature of the two businesses.
'We have different skills which would create a strong combined force in the
Scotch whisky industry. That is what our attempt to gain control of
Invergordon has been about. It is not a cost-cutting exercise.'
The combined companies would form the third largest Scotch producer.
Invergordon would contribute its strength in own-label Scotch, a rapidly
growing sector which is expected to account for 30 per cent of UK whisky
sales this year, as well as brands such as Cluny and Glayva liqueur. These
would be complemented by Whyte &amp; Mackay's Scotch whiskies, as well as
Vladivar vodka, and its bourbon and rum brands.
Lex, Page 20
</TEXT>
