<HEADLINE>
FT  22 OCT 93 / More NHS job losses planned: About 2,000 administrative
posts to go in proposed restructuring
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LARGE NUMBERS of National Health Service administrative jobs will be lost
under proposals to simplify the management structure announced by Mrs
Virginia Bottomley, health secretary, yesterday.
Unison, the public service union, estimated that the plans would mean 2,000
job losses in addition to 3,000 administrative posts that it says have gone
already this year.
Ministers say every effort will be made to minimise compulsory redundancies
when the 14 English regional health authorities are reduced to eight next
year and the service's Leeds-based management executive is slimmed down.
Mrs Bottomley was announcing her decisions on an internal review into the
higher level structure of the NHS now that the management of hospitals has
been devolved to local level.
The proposed eight amalgamated regions will have only a short life as
statutory authorities. Legislation to abolish regional authorities from 1996
will be introduced next year. The authorities will be replaced by regional
offices of the management executive, which is answerable to Mrs Bottomley
for the day-to-day running of the NHS.
Mrs Bottomley said she would limit the budgets of the management executive
and regional offices in order to 'bear down on administrative costs to
maximise spending on patients'. The existing regions and executive cost
Pounds 200m a year to run.
A battle over the extent to which the NHS needs direct government regulation
since the 1991 health reforms has been fought out behind the review.
Although the government said yesterday's plans were based on the review
committee's preferred option, the team offered more radical alternatives in
its report.
It suggested a formal separation between the Department of Health and the
NHS through the creation of an English National Health Authority, or that
the management executive could become an arm's-length agency.
Mrs Bottomley decided that separating the service from the department could
reduce parliamentary and public accountability. The management executive
will remain within the Department of Health but develop a more clearly
defined head office identity.
Even though Mrs Bottomley has taken a relatively cautious approach, critics
immediately accused her of further centralising the service and reducing
public accountability. Unison said the proposals were a denial of democracy
while Mr David Blunkett, shadow health secretary, said they were rampant
bureaucracy and would reduce accountability.
While regional health authorities are not elected, they have members
appointed to represent community interests. Critics fear the community link
would be undermined if they were replaced by Civil Service regional offices.
Mrs Bottomley intends to appoint a non-executive member from each of the
eight regions to sit on the NHS policy board in London. But this will not
satisfy campaigners for greater accountability.
Editorial Comment, Page 19
</TEXT>
