<HEADLINE>
FT  22 OCT 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICIA MORISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Public Eye: Cautionary Tales (BBC2, 8.00). The policy of cautioning
criminals for so-called minor offences, intended to stop reoffending, comes
under investigation. Is it right that 20-year-old Matt, having been
cautioned no fewer than 11 times, can break another man's jaw and not be
prosecuted?
Tonight is something of an event for gardeners, the first programme of a new
and genuinely different kind of gardening series, Plant Life (C4, 9.00).
It is perfectly possible to be a skilful gardener without understanding why
clay soil is sticky let alone having a clue about photosynthesis.
Yet many enthusiastic gardeners would probably do the outdoor jobs better
and possibly enjoy the gardening much more if they had a basic knowledge of
plant physiology and a clearer understanding of the relationship between the
plants and their environment.
Animated Arias: From Opera Imaginaire (BBC2, 9.50). The programmes have been
very different but also quite intriguing.
Tonight the treatment is applied to arias from Gounod's Faust and Puccini's
Tosca.
