<HEADLINE>
FT  22 OCT 93 / Big business techniques 'trickle down'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SOME of the financial benefits of new management techniques such as
just-in-time manufacturing are gradually trickling down from large companies
to small businesses, according to research by Manchester Business School.
Big companies are still using their financial muscle at the expense of
smaller businesses.
A regular six-monthly survey of 5,000 companies in north-west England shows
that 31 per cent of small businesses have increased their stock turnover
since the spring. This compared with only 24 per cent in the previous
survey.
The increase is attributed to a knock-on effect from larger companies, which
had reported faster stock turnover during the first six months of this year,
benefiting from the improvement in the economy. Modern management techniques
such as just-in-time manufacturing or electronic data interchange are being
used to encourage faster response times from suppliers in an attempt to to
keep all stocks and the money to finance them to a minimum.
Mr Nitin Sanghavi, who carried out the school's research under the
sponsorship of Price Waterhouse, the accountant, said: 'The encouraging
performance of smaller firms suggests these new techniques have improved
efficiency along the supply chain.' The research also shows, however, that
big companies are using their muscle to manage working capital more
efficiently at smaller companies' expense.
One in 10 large companies collect debts in less than 30 days, compared with
only 5 per cent of smaller ones; but 27 per cent of large companies succeed
in stretching credit past 60 days, while only 21 per cent of smaller
companies manage to do so. One result of better efficiency and improving
cashflow is that nearly 48 per cent of large companies have been able to
reduce borrowings in the last six months.
Business confidence has fallen sharply in the Midlands amid growing fears
that the recovery may be faltering, the Engineering Employers Federation
said yesterday.
According to its latest quarterly survey in the east Midlands, the
proportion of engineering companies reporting increased orders fell from 49
per cent in the three months to July to 32 per cent in the past quarter.
</TEXT>
<XX>
