<HEADLINE>
FT  22 OCT 93 / BR telecoms arm to be privatised
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS and IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH RAIL Telecommunications, a wholly-owned BR subsidiary, is to be sold
late next year. The government said it has the potential to compete with BT
and Mercury in the UK's telecoms market.
Announcing the sale yesterday, Mr John MacGregor, transport secretary, said
that responsibility for rail signalling safety would pass to Railtrack,
which will assume ownership of the rail network under the government's
privatisation plans.
Although BRT will continue to supply signalling, communications and business
services to the railway, Railtrack is likely to be free to employ other
private-sector suppliers, with BRT free to use spare capacity to sell to
other companies, provided it gains the necessary public licences.
In the year to April BRT had a gross income of Pounds 114m and made an
operating surplus of Pounds 22m. With cables running alongside 60,000 miles
of track, Mr MacGregor said BRT's network 'could be exploited for external
telecommunications customers'.
He added: 'There are excellent opportunities for private-sector involvement
in rail telecommunications while safeguarding operational requirements.' A
study of BRT's investment requirements is under way.
However, doubt was cast over the sell-off earlier this month with the sudden
departure of Mr Peter Borer, BRT's managing director.
Mr Borer is believed to have clashed with Sir Bob Reid, BR chairman, over
the sell-off plans. He had been attempting to promote a management buy-out
of BRT with a view to making it a national telecoms competitor. But the
necessary private-sector backing for the venture does not appear to have
been forthcoming.
The investment is necessary to extend the trackside lines to homes and
businesses. Telecoms operators including Singapore Telecom are believed to
have expressed interest, but to have gone no further.
Mr Tony Newton, leader of the House of Commons, refused to be drawn
yesterday on whether the government would seek to reverse the defeats it has
suffered in the House of Lords on the railways bill when it returns to the
Commons, Ivor Owen writes.
He said ministers were still considering the implications of amendments made
by peers which permit BR to seek franchises to operate passenger services,
and requiring the government to guarantee the solvency of the industry's
pension fund.
Mr Newton insisted that it would not be appropriate for him to make any
further comment until the consideration had been completed.
</TEXT>
