<HEADLINE>
FT  22 OCT 93 / Supercollider rushes to its doom: Hope ends for Higgs boson
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE US Congress yesterday finally pronounced the death sentence on the
superconducting supercollider, an Dollars 11bn (Pounds 7.2bn) particle
physics project being built in Texas.
The supercollider ' gigantic boondoggle or cutting edge science, depending
on your perspective ' often came close to losing its government funding, but
time and again it was pulled back from the edge of the grave by a handful of
powerful senators.
At last, however, it fell victim to a House-Senate conference committee's
desire for a closer match between deeds and budget-cutting rhetoric.
For two years, the House of Representatives voted overwhelmingly to kill the
supercollider, while the Senate voted to preserve it. For two years, the
conference to reconcile the two versions of the bill bowed to the Senate.
This time-honoured technique had the advantage of enabling members to tell
their constituents that they voted to cut spending, safe in the knowledge
that the project would be restored behind the conference's closed doors.
This year, however, House members revolted and sent back the reconciled bill
by an overwhelming vote of 282 to 143. Supercollider supporters, led by
Texas, where the project is sited, and Louisiana, where its giant magnets
are being built, yesterday acknowledged the inevitable.
As a consolation prize, under an agreement reached yesterday by House and
Senate negotiators, they won Dollars 640m to close the project down and pay
off its scientists ' as much as they had asked for this year to keep it
alive.
The supercollider was intended to take physics a step into the future by
accelerating proton beams around a 54 mile oval tunnel lined with magnets,
smashing them together at close to the speed of light in the hope of
producing the Higgs boson, a small particle one stage beyond the quark whose
existence is theorised.
Around Dollars 2bn has already been spent and 14 miles of tunnel have been
dug, but the supercollider's estimated completion cost had climbed rapidly
from Dollars 4.4bn in 1987 to Dollars 11bn this year.
Senator Dale Bumpers of Arkansas waged a long battle against the
supercollider, made more piquant by the fact that his foes included many of
the Senate's loudest proponents of budget austerity.
'I do not see how anybody can keep a straight face and talk about spending
cuts, then  ..vote for the supercollider. I've got a dog with a longer
memory than the US Senate,' Mr Bumpers complained.
This year, however, the Congress showed more determination to come to grips
with the US budget deficit.
Some congressional traditions are safe, nevertheless: the House-Senate
reconciliation conference on the energy and water spending bill which
contained the supercollider restored to life every other project which one
chamber or the other had voted to kill.
</TEXT>
<XX>
