<HEADLINE>
FT  22 OCT 93 / Political shake-up for Canada
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
CONSERVATIVES
Party promises to eradicate the CDollars 35bn budget deficit within five
years without raising taxes or jeopardising health-care spending. Would
probably reappoint the inflation-fighting John Crow as Bank of Canada
governor. Would implement North American Free Trade Agreement (Nafta). Plans
no major change in immigration policy.
LIBERALS
Party pledges to reduce budget deficit from 5.2 per cent of GDP to 3 per
cent. Would try to renegotiate Nafta. Plans to stimulate the economy with a
CDollars 2bn public works programme and youth training. Would replace 7 per
cent goods and services tax with unspecified 'fairer' tax. Would cancel
order for 43 European EH-101 helicopters.
NDP
Party vigorously opposes Nafta. Would try to replace the US-Canada pact with
sectoral agreements. Would reduce budget deficit by chopping defence
spending by 3 per cent a year and raising taxes on companies and wealthy
individuals. Would replace goods and services tax.
BLOC QUEBECOIS
Party's long-term goal is independence for Quebec. Meanwhile, promises to
put Quebec's interests first but without disrupting parliament. Proposes to
cut CDollars 10bn from budget and reinvest CDollars 5bn in job-creation
programme. Supports free trade and proposes measures such as retraining to
ease transition.
REFORM
Party plans to eliminate the budget deficit in three years. Would cut
unemployment insurance, old age security benefits and business subsidies.
Supports Nafta, provided Canada would have more control over water
resources. Opposes special treatment for Quebec, and would cut immigration
by a third.
