<HEADLINE>
FT  22 OCT 93 / Commonwealth takes up trade reform struggle
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL HOLMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LIMASSOL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
COMMONWEALTH leaders yesterday opened their five-day summit in Cyprus,
stressing the urgent need for a new international trade agreement and
reaffirming their commitment to human rights.
Australian Prime Minister Paul Keating used his first appearance at the
forum to make an attack, clearly aimed at France, on countries holding up
progress in the Uruguay Round of trade liberalisation talks, while leaving
no doubt his country's move to republican status would not undermine its
Commonwealth ties.
In a speech designed to refocus the 50-member association in the wake of
apartheid's demise, Chief Emeka Anyaoku, its secretary-general, made trade
reform a priority.
He linked the outcome of the Uruguay Round talks to efforts to promote
democracy within the Commonwealth and elsewhere. 'Like armies, democracies
march on their stomachs. The successful conclusion of the Uruguay Round
promises an annual addition to global income of Dollars 213bn by the year
2002,' Chief Anyaoku told the heads of government.
'Yet that crucial step now looks uncertain, threatening not merely the loss
of the huge potential gains but a spiralling descent into protectionism and
isolationism.'
Mr Keating's contribution was the first stage in a co-ordinated effort by
Australia and Britain to enlist support for trade reform from an association
whose membership spans Francophone Africa, the Cairns group and many of the
world's poorest countries.
Taking the offensive in the opening session, Mr Keating warned: 'Time is
very short for us to prevent the Round's collapse.' Clearly referring to
France, he went on: 'Some 'rich countries' still seem to believe they can
avoid making difficult concessions but still reap the advantages of the
Round. I think they are completely wrong, and are likely to bear the
opprobrium and contumely of the whole world.'
Mr John Major, UK prime minister, made the issue the centre of his
contribution later in the day, when the conference went into closed session.
He echoed Mr Keating's call on Commonwealth leaders to 'make every effort to
examine what the Commonwealth can do to help bring about an outcome from the
Multilateral Trade Negotiations to benefit each of us and the world at
large.'
Mr Major also highlighted the problem of third world debt, conceding that
more needed to be done to ease the burden on developing countries. In
particular, he called for rapid implementation of the Trinidad terms, which
provide for a write-off of 50 per cent of official debt.
But he went further by holding out the prospect of improved Trinidad terms.
'The neediest countries, with a track record of economic reform, should be
granted two-thirds debt reduction on their whole stock of official debt,' he
said. 'In some cases this should be a high as 80 per cent.'
Mr Major added that in all too many places 'the age of the warlord is
returning', placing greater demands on the Commonwealth and the UN. But
objectives must be realistic and linked to a political process. 'What we
cannot do, we should not pretend to do. But what we decide to do, we must do
well.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>CYZ  Cyprus, Middle East.
</CN>
