<HEADLINE>
FT  22 OCT 93 / Dutch praise for caution on rates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   AMSTERDAM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Wim Duisenberg, the president of the Netherlands National Bank, last
night stressed that yesterday's cuts in Bundesbank and other European
interest rates did not represent any change in the cautious monetary
policies of continental central banks.
Addressing a group of international monetary policy makers and academics, Mr
Duisenberg castigated 'Anglo-Saxon commentators' for failing to understand
that sharp cuts in short-term interest rates would not boost the
recession-hit member countries of the European exchange rate mechanism.
Mr Duisenberg, who is also chairman of the European Community's central bank
governors' committee, said attempts to force down short-term interest rates
aggressively 'might very well stir up inflationary expectations again' and
result in higher rather than lower long-term interest rates.
Long-term rates were 'far more important for investment and growth than
short-term rates' among ERM member states, he said. 'In the short run,
changes in short-term interest rates in continental Europe do not have a
large impact on the disposable income of consumers and enterprises.' Such
effects as there were only appeared after a long time lag.
Mr Duisenberg underlined that monetary stability in a European context meant
more than price stability. It also meant exchange rate stability.
'This is a fact I cannot over-emphasise,' he said. 'Sometimes, the crucial
notion of exchange rate stability as an essential foundation of the
functioning of the single internal European market is strongly
underestimated. In the very open and highly interdependent continental
European economies, ex-change rate volatility is much more damaging to trade
and general economic developments than in, for instance, the United States.'
He applauded how ERM central banks had steered clear of competitive
devaluations in the aftermath of the July and August currency crisis that
resulted in the widening of most ERM fluctuation margins to 15 per cent
either side of central rates.
The cautious approach to short-term interest rates cuts had paid off.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>NLZ  Netherlands, EC.
</CN>
