<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Sweden's central bank cut its key interest rate yesterday in a further
attempt to pull the country's economy out of its worst recession since 1945,
writes Christopher Brown-Humes in Stockholm. The reduction from 8 per cent
to 7.75 per cent is the latest in a series of cuts which has brought the
bank's marginal rate down from 12.5 per cent last November before the
Swedish krona was floated. The cut was made before the Bundesbank decided to
lower German interest rates.
