<HEADLINE>
FT  21 OCT 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Compaq and Digital send mixed
messages
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HAVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US SHARE prices traded in a narrow range either side of opening values
yesterday as the equity markets continued to digest the latest third-quarter
corporate earnings news, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 9.78 at 3,645.10. The
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 ended 0.14 easier at 466.07, while the American SE
composite finished 0.49 firmer at 476.59 and the Nasdaq composite off 0.46
at 768.25. NYSE volume reached 307m shares.
After several weeks of steady gains, and two days of heavy profit-taking,
the markets appear to be at a crossroads. In the absence of fresh economic
news, equity investors struggled to find a new direction yesterday. The bond
market was in solid form - the yield on the benchmark 30-year bond has
dropped to 5.821 per cent - but it failed to provide stocks with much
support.
Consequently, trading was uninspired and prices hovered around opening
values throughout the day. Overnight strength in foreign markets was largely
ignored and investors' attention was primarily fixed upon the latest batch
of quarterly results.
Among those reporting yesterday were two big technology companies, Digital
Equipment and Compaq. The former announced a wider than expected quarterly
loss, driving its shares down Dollars 1 to Dollars 35 1/8 . Compaq, however,
surpassed analysts' forecasts with its own profits announcement, and the
stock climbed Dollars 2 1/2 to Dollars 64 7/8 .
AMR, parent of American Airlines, rose Dollars 1 to Dollars 68 after the
group reported net income of Dollars 1.33 a share, a strong recovery from
the Dollars 1.32 a share loss incurred at the same stage a year ago. USAir,
however, was steady at Dollars 13 3/4 as investors were left unimpressed by
its third-quarter loss of Dollars 178m.
Bank stocks, hard hit by profit-taking and concern about lower lending rates
cutting into profit margins, rebounded handsomely. Citicorp advanced Dollars
1 5/8 to Dollars 37 3/8 , JP Morgan added Dollars  7/8 at Dollars 72 7/8 and
Chemical put on Dollars  1/2 at Dollars 41 3/8 . BankAmerica eased Dollars
1/8 to Dollars 42 1/2 after reporting flat third-quarter earnings.
Tobacco shares were weaker, undermined by reports that President Bill
Clinton has decided upon a 75 cents a pack increase in the cigarette tax.
Philip Morris shed Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 51 7/8 , American Brands gave up
Dollars  3/4 at Dollars 33 5/8 and RJR Nabisco eased Dollars  1/8 to Dollars
4 7/8 .
On the Nasdaq market, Microsoft rose initially and then fell before rallying
to end a net Dollars  3/4 up at Dollars 81, as investors nervously awaited
the third-quarter results, which were due out after the close.
Canada
TORONTO finished slightly higher after busy trading. The TSE 300 index
gained 7.6 at 4,182.2 and rises outnumbered declines by 382 to 359. Volume
was 67.7m shares.
Despite the index rise, however, 10 of the 14 sub-indices were lower, led by
transportation, off 1.5 per cent. Golds climbed 2.7 per cent as the New York
bullion price rose USDollars 3.55 to USDollars 372.55 an ounce.
</TEXT>
