<HEADLINE>
FT  21 OCT 93 / World Commodities Prices: Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The GOLD reached a two-month high as fresh US investor fund buying piled
into the New York futures markets. In London it closed at Dollars 372 a troy
ounce, up Dollars 5 on the day. 'It is quite a strong move. The (investment)
funds are buying it fairly heavily,' one dealer said, adding there was no
physical demand. 'Dealers were buying to test the price at over Dollars
370,' he said. SILVER was also strong, ending 13 cents up at Dollars 4.51
1/2 an ounce, but Platinum lagged with a Dollars 1.85 rise to Dollars 375.10
an ounce. At the London Metal Exchange the three months TIN price rose to a
fresh 10-week high of Dollars 4,970 a tonne but found expected stiff
resistance near Dollars 5,000 and ended after hours trading at Dollars 4,950
a tonne, up Dollars 70 on balance. COPPER ended its decline with three
months metal gaining Dollars 12.75 to Dollars 1,645.25 a tonne in what
dealers described as a 'technical consolidation'. ZINC was unable to extend
initial upward momentum, with the rise attracting hedge selling, although an
undercurrent of support remained, based on continued talk of production
cuts. The three months price closed at Dollars 952.50 a tonne, up Dollars
11.
Compiled from Reuters
</TEXT>
