FT  21 OCT 93 / International Company News: Lower oil prices restrict Texaco
to Dollars 317m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WEAKER oil prices and special items restricted third-quarter net income on
continuing operations at Texaco to Dollars 317m, or Dollars 1.13 a share,
compared with Dollars 325m, or Dollars 1.26 a share, a year before.
Including the loss on the sale of the company's chemical business, net
income fell to Dollars 142m.
Before all one-off items, after-tax earnings were Dollars 255m, down from
Dollars 338m the previous year. Mr Alfred DeCrane, chairman and chief
executive, said this reflected a 'solid performance' in the face of a
Dollars 4 per barrel decline in crude oil prices.
Operating earnings from US exploration and production fell from Dollars 193m
to Dollars 138m while upstream activities overseas generated Dollars 15m,
down from Dollars 98m (both before special items), largely as a result of
lower oil prices.
Operating income from downstream businesses, on the other hand, rose to
Dollars 99m from Dollars 83m in the US and remained flat at Dollars 107m
overseas.
Texaco also reported special charges of Dollars 235m, stemming from staff
reductions, reserves to meet environmental clean-up costs and asset
write-downs.
These were offset by a Dollars 152m credit due to a change in tax law
affecting deferred taxes and a Dollars 145m deferred tax credit related to
the sale of an interest in a subsidiary.
A loss on the sale of Texaco's chemical operations led to a Dollars 164m
charge, along with a Dollars 11m loss for the quarter on the chemical
business.
