and a slowdown in the sneaker market, AP-DJ reports.
The US group earned Dollars 63.9m, or 74 cents a share, for the three-month
period, compared with Dollars 74.3m, or 80 cents, in the same period last
year.
This year's figure included after-tax losses of Dollars 7m stemming from the
recently-completed sales of its Boston Whaler and Ellesse subsidiaries.
Revenue for the quarter dropped to Dollars 808.5m from Dollars 863.2m in
last year.
Last year's sales figures included revenue from Boston Whaler and Ellesse.
But even excluding those numbers, sales would have fallen by 3.6 per cent
this year.
The decline was brought on largely by a drop in the Reebok footwear
business.
In the US market, the company said quarterly sales of Reebok footwear fell
by around 20 per cent, reflecting the sluggish economy and a change in
footwear styles away from sneakers as casual shoes.
For the first nine months of 1993, Reebok reported profits of Dollars
172.7m, or Dollars 1.94, down from Dollars 182.4m, or Dollars 1.96 a year
earlier. Nine-month sales were Dollars 2.29n, compared with Dollars 2.36bn.
