<HEADLINE>
FT  21 OCT 93 / Dasa plans closures and staff cuts to return to the black
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
DEUTSCHE Aerospace (Dasa), the aircraft, defence and satellites division of
Daimler-Benz, is to shut six German sites, shed non-core activities and make
further heavy cuts in its workforce by the end of 1996.
The restructuring will save the loss-making company DM1.5bn (Pounds 611m) a
year, Mr Jurgen Schrempp, chairman, claimed yesterday. The aim was to return
to profit in 1995.
Turnover this year would be DM1.2bn lower than the DM16bn originally
envisaged, he said, and new orders would be DM3bn down.
Mr Schrempp, a dogged defender of the Eurofighter joint venture, has often
complained of lack of support from Bonn. A new report on the four-nation
warplane venture by the national audit office, due to reach the defence
ministry soon, criticises the project for poor management and excessive
costs.
'But the question remains whether and to what extent those people who have
an essential influence on the economic and political environment are
prepared to make their contribution to the continuance of the aerospace
industry in Germany,' he said.
Dasa's defence sales, which in 1991 accounted for 50 per cent of turnover,
generate only 27 per cent now. Federal spending on military hardware of
DM12bn a year in 1990, is scheduled to fall to DM6bn next year.
Two of the sites earmarked for closure are part of Dasa's Airbus commercial
airliner business, the other four are all defence-related. Company
executives said only 120 Airbuses would be built next year, compared with
original plans for 216.
Businesses scheduled for disposal are believed to include Dornier medical
technology, while Dasa is to attempt to bolster its guided missiles arm
through a joint venture with France. The company already has close links
with Aerospatiale.
News of the cuts immediately stirred protests, notably from the government
of Lower Saxony, where Dasa's Lemwerder aircraft maintenance site, employing
1,136, is to close.
Dasa workers' councils are also understood to be angry over alleged lack of
consultation.
