FT  21 OCT 93 / Letters to the Editor: Corporate capital has adverse impact
on Names
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr ALAN J LEBOFF
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, In spite of my children and myself having lost a fortune at Lloyd's, we
ignored the pleas of a number of action groups and submitted our proxies in
favour of the chairman at yesterday's meeting (and therefore in support of
the introduction of corporate capital). We did so on the basis of the many
communications we have received assuring us that corporate capital is
essential for the health and future of Lloyd's and that it will in no way
adversely affect the interests of existing Names.
Yesterday morning, I received by post from my underwriting agents a fuller
explanation for the substantial, unexpected additional cash call they made
last week, saying: 'The cash calls . . .stem from the decision of Lloyd's to
discontinue cross lending by syndicates within the Lloyd's American Trust
Fund. . . in anticipation of the arrival of corporate capital in 1994.'
If asking me to pay yet more money now 'in anticipation of' corporate
capital in 1994 is not being 'affected adversely', what would be? You may be
sure that had Lloyd's made the choice plain, 'vote for corporate capital and
it will cost you', we would have voted against. How do we get it across to
those in power there is a limit to the money Names can find and that should
be their first priority, not the shape in which Lloyd's will enter the 21st
century?
Alan J Leboff,
Andelain,
South Park Crescent,
Gerrards Cross,
Buckinghamshire SL9 8HJ
